===Verb===
{{en-verb|abhorr}}

# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To regard with [[horror]] or [[detestation]]; to [[shrink]] back with [[shudder]]ing from; to feel excessive [[repugnance]] toward; to [[detest]] to extremity; to [[loathe]]. {{defdate|First attested from around (1350 to 1470).}}<ref name=SOED>{{R:SOED5|page=4}}</ref>
#* '''1611''', Romans 12:9, {{w|Authorized King James Version|King James Bible}}:
#*: '''Abhor''' that which is evil; cleave to that which is good.
# {{context|transitive|obsolete|impersonal|lang=en}} To fill with horror or [[disgust]]. {{defdate|Attested from the mid 16<sup>th</sup> century until the early 17<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
#* '''c. 1604''' {{w|William Shakespeare}}, ''Othello'', act 4, scene 1:
#*: It does '''abhor''' me now I speak the word.
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To turn aside or avoid; to keep away from; to reject.
# {{context|transitive|canon law|obsolete|lang=en}} To [[protest]] against; to reject [[solemnly]].
#* '''c. 1613''' {{w|William Shakespeare}}, ''Henry VIII'', act 2, scene 4:
#*: I utterly '''abhor''', yea, from my soul Refuse you for my judge.
# {{context|intransitive|obsolete|lang=en}} To [[shrink]] back with horror, [[disgust]], or [[dislike]]; to be [[contrary]] or [[averse]]; {{non-gloss definition|construed with ''from''}}. {{defdate|Attested from the mid 16<sup>th</sup> century until the mid 17<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
#* {{rfquotek|Udall}}:
#*: To '''abhor''' from those vices.
#* {{rfquotek|Milton}}:
#*: Which is utterly '''abhorring''' from the end of all law.
# {{context|intransitive|obsolete|lang=en}} Differ entirely from. {{defdate|Attested from the mid 16<sup>th</sup> century until the late 17<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>

